1 age which is false, fraudulent, or not actually his or her own, for the purpose of purchasing or
2 receiving any tobacco product or cigarette wrapping papers, the person shall be guilty of a Class
3 2 misdemeanor; provided, however, that it shall not be unlawful for an employee to purchase or
4 accept receipt of tobacco products or cigarette wrapping papers when required in the performance
5 of the employee's duties.
6 (d) Sending or Assisting a Person [Less Than] 18 21 Years to Purchase or Receive
7 Tobacco Products or Cigarette Wrapping Papers. – If any person shall send a person less than 18
8 21 years of age to purchase, acquire, receive, or attempt to purchase, acquire, or receive tobacco
9 products or cigarette wrapping papers, or if any person shall aid or abet a person who is less than
10 18 21 years of age in purchasing, acquiring, or receiving or attempting to purchase, acquire, or
11 receive tobacco products or cigarette wrapping papers, the person shall be guilty of a Class 2
12 misdemeanor; provided, however, persons under the age of 18 21 may be enlisted by police or
13 local sheriffs' departments to test compliance if the testing is under the direct supervision of that
14 law enforcement department and written parental consent is provided; provided further, that the
15 Department of Health and Human Services shall have the authority, pursuant to a written plan
16 prepared by the Secretary of Health and Human Services, to use persons under 18 21 years of
17 age in annual, random, unannounced inspections, provided that prior written parental consent is
18 given for the involvement of these persons and that the inspections are conducted for the sole
19 purpose of preparing a scientifically and methodologically valid statistical study of the extent of
20 success the State has achieved in reducing the availability of tobacco products to persons under
21 the age of 18, 21, and preparing any report to the extent required by section 1926 of the federal
22 Public Health Service Act (42 USC § 300x-26).
23 …."
24 SECTION 1.1.(b) This Part becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
25 offenses committed on or after that date.
26
27 PART II. REVISIONS TO BROADEN THE VAPOR PRODUCTS LICENSE
28 REQUIREMENT
29 SECTION 2.1.(a) G.S. 105-113.39A(a2) reads as rewritten:
30 "(a2) Vapor Products License. – A wholesale dealer or a retail dealer must obtain a vapor
31 products license for all of the following locations:
32 (1) Each location where a wholesale dealer makes vapor products.
33 (2) Each location where a wholesale dealer or a retail dealer receives or stores
34 non-tax-paid vapor products.
35 (3) Each location from where a retail dealer that is a delivery seller or a remote
36 seller receives or stores non-tax-paid vapor products for delivery sales if the
37 location is a location other than the location described in subdivision (2) of
38 this subsection.
39 (4) Each location from where a retail dealer receives or stores tax-paid vapor
40 products if the location is a location other than the location described in
41 subdivision (2) of this subsection."
42 SECTION 2.1.(b) This Part becomes effective December 1, 2025.
43
44 PART III. FUNDING FOR GAMBLING ADDICTION EDUCATION AND
45 TREATMENT PROGRAMS THROUGH GAMING REVENUES COLLECTED BY THE
46 LOTTERY COMMISSION
47 SECTION 3.1. G.S. 105-113.128 reads as rewritten:
48 "§ 105-113.128. Use of tax proceeds.
49 The Secretary shall distribute the taxes collected under this Article, less the allowance to the
50 Department of Revenue and reimbursement to the Lottery Commission for administrative
51 expenses, in accordance with this section. The Secretary may retain the cost of administering this
Senate Bill 533-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Article, not to exceed five hundred thousand dollars ($500,000) a year, as reimbursement to the
2 Department. The Lottery Commission shall, no later than 20 days after the end of the month,
3 notify the Department of its unreimbursed expenses from administering the provisions of Article
4 9 of Chapter 18C of the General Statutes from the previous month. The Department shall
5 reimburse the Lottery Commission from the tax revenues collected under this Article no later
6 than the end of the month in which the Department was notified. The remainder of the net
7 proceeds of the tax collected under this Article are to be credited in the following priority:
8 (1) Two Twelve million dollars ($2,000,000) ($12,000,000) annually to the
9 Department of Health and Human Services for the following:
10 a. Five million four hundred thousand dollars ($5,400,000) for gambling
11 addiction education and treatment programs.programs and recovery
12 support services.
13 b. Four million two hundred thousand dollars ($4,200,000) for
14 prevention initiatives, including school-based programs.
15 c. Two million four hundred thousand dollars ($2,400,000) for a
16 statewide public awareness campaign.
17 …."
18 SECTION 3.2.(a) From the tax proceeds credited to the Department of Health and
19 Human Services pursuant to G.S. 105-113.128, as amended by this act, the Department of Health
20 and Human Services shall do all of the following:
21 (1) Develop a statewide public awareness campaign about gambling addiction. In
22 developing this campaign, the Department shall consult with addiction
23 specialists and individuals who have lived experience with gambling
24 addiction to (i) develop materials and initiatives to raise public awareness
25 about the risks, potential harms, and addictive nature of gambling and (ii)
26 promote resources for the prevention and treatment of gambling addiction.
27 The statewide public awareness campaign shall include at least all of the
28 following components:
29 a. Factual, evidence-based information about gambling addiction risks
30 and warning signs.
31 b. Specific messaging about youth gambling and digital gambling
32 platforms.
33 c. Real stories and testimonials from North Carolinians affected by
34 gambling addiction.
35 d. Clear information about how to access treatment and support services
36 for gambling addiction.
37 e. Availability of information in multiple languages reflecting North
38 Carolina's diverse population.
39 f. Targeted messaging for high-risk populations as identified by current
40 research.
41 g. Utilization of multiple media channels, including social media,
42 television, radio, and community-based outreach.
43 (2) Establish and administer a grant program that awards directed grants on a
44 competitive basis to nonprofit organizations to implement or expand
45 evidence-based gambling prevention and treatment programs. The
46 Department of Health and Human Services shall develop an application
47 process and eligibility criteria for the grant program authorized by this
48 subdivision.
49 (3) Expand access to treatment programs and services for individuals and families
50 affected by gambling addiction.
Page 4 Senate Bill 533-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Support gambling prevention initiatives targeting students in grades K-12,
2 including efforts to raise awareness about gambling addiction among students
3 and provide educational resources on the risks associated with gambling.
4 SECTION 3.2.(b) Annually by February 28, beginning February 28, 2026, the
5 Department of Health and Human Services shall report to the Joint Legislative Oversight
6 Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division on the use of the tax
7 proceeds credited to the Department of Health and Human Services pursuant to
8 G.S. 105-113.128, as amended by this act. The report shall include, at a minimum, all of the
9 following information for the preceding fiscal year:
10 (1) The number of grants awarded under Section 3.2(a)(2) of this act, the identity
11 and a brief description of each grantee, and the amount of grant funds awarded
12 to each grantee.
13 (2) An itemized list of gambling addiction treatment programs and services
14 funded by these proceeds and for each, an itemized list of expenditures.
15 (3) The number of individuals served by each program or receiving services
16 described in subdivision (2) of this subsection.
17 (4) An evaluation of the effectiveness of the programs and services funded by
18 these proceeds using objective performance evaluation metrics.
19 SECTION 3.2.(c) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to gross
20 wagering revenue received on or after that date.
21
22 PART IV. EFFECTIVE DATE
23 SECTION 4.1. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
24 law.
